{
  "doc_id": "11151",
  "text": "Multiple Sclerosis (MS) is a chronic autoimmune disease of the Central Nervous System (CNS) causing inflammation and neurodegeneration. The characteristic demyelination of the neurons, followed in many cases by axonal loss and gliosis, results in incapacity progression [CITATION_1] . The incapacity status is usually assessed in MS patients with the Expanded Disability Status Scale (EDSS) [CITATION_2] . Different types of MS have been described based on the clinical course: Relapsing-Remitting Multiple Sclerosis (RRMS), Secondary Progressive Multiple Sclerosis (SPMS), Primary Progressive Multiple Sclerosis (PPMS), Relapsing-Progressing Multiple Sclerosis (RPMS) [CITATION_3] and Clinically Isolated Syndrome (CIS) [CITATION_4] .",
